on Tue, 03 Oct 89 10:44:39 -0400,
jb@cs.brown.edu said:

jb&gt; Over the past couple months, I have seen sri-nic.arpa, brl-aos.arpa
jb&gt; and gunter-adam.arpa (yes, I mean the old names for these hosts)
jb&gt; being listed as root servers.  I found one source of these and it
jb&gt; seems to have been fixed, but there must be others.  What prompted
jb&gt; this note was receiving these from one of the root servers today.

...

jb&gt; My guess is that these address are originating on hosts running old
jb&gt; versions of BIND and loading an incorrect list of root servers.  These
jb&gt; then get propogated from there by servers not being able to answer a
jb&gt; query that was refered to them.  I realize that BIND should really
jb&gt; be fixed to be less trusting in what it adds to its cache but that
jb&gt; won't do anyting about those people running 2 year old software.


Is bind 4.8 considered to be ``old''?  I found these bogus entries
in my root.cache, straight out of bind 4.8.  In any case, they've
been corrected here.

Stephen Pope
Santa Fe Institute
scp@sfi.santafe.edu

